POLYMORPHISMS, RLFPS, SNPS AND PATHOGENICITY
1.Finding a Phenotype for a SNP
Case: You are working with the sequence variation rs2068824. This is a Single
Nucleotide Polymorphism (SNP) located in the MMEL1 gene in human. The gene codes
for a metalloprotease that cleaves polypeptides preferentially between hydrophobic
residues.
Task: This sequence variation has shown up in several of your samples in patients
with digestive troubles. Use Ensembl to find out if any phenotypes or diseases are
known to be associated with this SNP.
RESULTS:
a) What Phenotype is associated with this SNP?
The SNP rs2068824 is associated with Celiac Disease
b) What gene is affected and how?
The Nav1 gene is affected due to a transcript variant occurring within an intron.
c) Where did the association come from and what is the PMID for the publication?
The association comes from GWAS,dbSNP and the PMID for the publication is 23936387: “A possible
mechanism behind autoimmune disorders discovered by genome-wide linkage and association
analysis in celiac disease.”

2. Human population genetics and phenotype data.
a. In which transcripts is this SNP found?
rs1349707492, rs1779875301, rs867562727
b. What is the least frequent genotype for this SNP in the Yoruba (YRI) population from the
1000 Genomes phase 3?
C|T: 0.463
c. What is the ancestral allele? Is it conserved in the 91 eutherian mammals?
Allele that is certainly not a determined allele. Hereditary allele isn't characterized by close life
forms. Yes it is conserved in 91 eutherian mammals.
d. With which diseases is this SNP associated? Are there any known risk (or associated)
alleles?
White blood cell count, Celiac diseases.
It can cause abdominal pain and bloating.
3. Exploring a SNP in human
(a) Find the page with information for rs1801133.
https://www.ensembl.org/Homo_sapiens/Variation/Explore?r=1:11795821-
11796821;v=rs1801133;vdb=variation;vf=1280266
(b) Is rs1801133 a Missense variation in all transcripts of the MTHFR gene? What is the amino
acid change?
No. The AC changes is A:27.3, C:23.1
(c) Why are the alleles for this variation in Ensembl given as G/A and not as C/T, as in the
literature?
The aleles are reference alternative alleles.
(d) What is the major allele in rs1801133?
Answer. G
(e) In which paper(s) is the association between rs1801133 and homocysteine levels
described?
- http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC8047106
- http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC8073279
- http://europepmc.org/articles/PMC8189424
